        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In order to achieve our goal, we need the sensitivity that is high enough to accurately measure the mass of dust and gas in the disk. We request to use the most extended antenna configuration with the synthesized beam size of 0.12" at Band 7. This beam size allows us to resolve the structure of ~ 22 AU in size so the expected asymmetric structure can be safely detected.
As shown in Figure 2, we expect a good quality imaging data that can distinguish the intrinsic asymmetric structure. The imaging simulation was done for a single pointing without ACA. ACA is not required for our observation since the structure we are interested is like a point source (mostly within 1.5" in diameter). T56 is suited for gas observations since our wide field of observation (7.8' x 7.8') shows no contamination from the ambient clouds. CO (3-2) will be suitable for tracing gas disk structure because it is optically thick and can detect diffused gas. HCO+ (4-3) will be simultaneously observed, which is useful for tracing gas at inner region and strong for contamination, not like CO lines (Casassus et al. 2013). MM-sized dust information can be obtained by thermal continuum emission and its distribution can be compared with theμm-sized dust distribution.    
Considering the realistic observational time in Cycle 2, we aim at the sensitivity of 4mJy/beam at CO (3-2) line with the velocity resolution of 0.212km/s. This corresponds to the observation of 1.93 hour on source and 4.51 hour in total as a result of ALMA Observing Tool calculator. With this velocity resolution, the Keplerian motion within 100 AU is well resolved. This sensitivity allows us to detect the high velocity component (2.4 km/s relative to the systemic velocity), which might originate from the inner part of the disk (Kim et al. 2009). Therefore, this requested sensitivity and the angular resolution is sufficient to probe the gas and dust component of the disk.
Our observational setup also allows us to observe the dust continuum with the sensitivity down to approximately 0.03 mJy/beam when 4 GHz bandwidth is used. This means that it is capable of detecting a typical disk around low-mass star, for example GM Aur has 65mJy per SMA beam of 0.32” x 0.27” (Andrews et al. 2011). As a result, the expected asymmetric structure can be safely detected with high signal-to-noise ratio, if it exists.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
